<DOC><DOCNO> AP881018-0248 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-88 1118EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     10-18 0245</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0260</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market was higher in moderate tradingearly today, buoyed by takeover activity surrounding several bigfood companies.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 4.27 at 2,144.74at 11 a.m. EDT, reversing an initial decline.   Advancing stocks were ahead of declining ones by around 3-to-2,with 625 issues higher, 479 lower and 567 unchanged.   Volume on the Big Board totaled 55.63 million shares.   Analysts said most of the action centered around issues of majorfood companies involved in new takeover bids.   ``The rest of the market is still on hold,'' said HildegardeZagorski, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.   Kraft stock had shot up 27] a share to 87{ in heavy trading,just below the $90 a share offered late Monday by Philip Morris inan $11 billion takeover offer. Philip Morris stock had dropped 4|to 95], apparently because investors felt the acquisition woulddilute the earnings of the cigarette and food giant.   Philip Morris said it has filed suit against Kraft and certainof its directors in an Illinois court.   In another major development in the food industry, Pillsbury wasdown \ at 58]. Pillsbury said its board of directors unanimouslyrejected a $60-a-share tender offer from Grand Metropolitan ofBritain.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks wasup 0.74 at 156.61.   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index hadslipped 0.04 to 303.23.</TEXT></DOC>